1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,500
Just talk to your terminal — in plain language.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:14,500
And Fusion 360 starts moving on its own.

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:24,500
Today we'll build a robot arm by chatting with GitHub Copilot CLI plus an MCP server.

4
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,500
Build a robot arm — with words.

5
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,500
The setup is simple.

6
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:47,500
Copilot CLI turns my words into Fusion 360 API calls through the MCP server.

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:59,500
Launch Copilot CLI, and we're ready. Let's start building.

8
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:14,500
First, the base. A cylinder, 6 cm radius, 2 cm tall.

9
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:14,500
Done. It even named the body "Base" for us.

10
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:24,500
Next, a yaw-axis cylinder on top of the base.

11
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,500
Stacked at the right spot in one shot.

12
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:41,500
Now the upper arm — a box, with fillets in the same prompt.

13
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:49,500
Even fine details work in plain language.

14
00:01:50,000 --> 00:02:01,500
The elbow pivot is a cylinder along the Y axis.

15
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:09,500
Axis directions are understood without code.

16
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:21,500
Forearm — another box, on top of the elbow.

17
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:29,500
It's starting to look like a real arm.

18
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:44,500
Last, a two-finger gripper.

19
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:59,500
Six prompts — and a full robot arm is assembled.

20
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:14,500
Geometry alone is boring. Let's add joints.

21
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:24,500
Revolute joints on the yaw axis and the elbow.

22
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:39,500
And it moves — just like a real robot.

23
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:49,500
Finally, export to F3D and STL — ready for printing or any other CAD.

24
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:54,500
Natural language → CAD.

25
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,500
That's what Copilot CLI plus MCP can do.
